<br>
I would like to elaborate on two of your points.<br>
<br>
First:  Miracles<br>
<br>
Actually, what contemporary people call 'miracles' appear quite frequently in Buddhist traditions.  My former kickboxing trainer is actually a Taoist priest and spent a great deal of time in Southeast Asia.  He has seen levitation, telekinesis, laying on of hands, and other acts which are simply manipulations of chi.  Western science is very quick to dismiss this as hooplah because it can't be quantifiably measured.<br>
<br>
This is an exercise in imagination:<br>
1) Pretend that CHI, or some other power like it exists. (the force even)<br>
2) Pretend this force is in everything and makes up everything.<br>
3) Now, pretend that this force can be manipulated, just as modern physics allows us to manipulate the laws of physics.  Who would have thought a 100 ton piece of steel could fly through the sky?  <br>
4) Pretend that this invisible force can be manipulated by educated &quot;chi-scientists&quot; who understand the nature of this force, just like regular scientists understand the nature of atoms, quarks, and particles.<br>
5) Now, pretend that given enough knowledge and practice at it, these &quot;chi-scientists&quot; can manipulate the force and create effects which we would call miracles.<br>
6) Pretend that by chanting in a particular tone with repition, and the proper bodily and environmental conditions, this force stuff could be channeled into something, such as creating a ray of blue light, curing the sick, or causing something to levitate.<br>
<br>
This exercise in imagination is to provoke the idea that the possibilty of 'miracles' is REAL, and that modern science COULD explain them, given enough time, and a proper mindset.<br>
I firmly believe that the universe is ordered by <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> GOD</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> and his physics, and that humans are well on our way to understanding these physics, as evidenced by modern technology.  God himself performs miracles by manipulation of these physics, albeit on a level we can't quite understand.  In this sense, the universe is JUST LIKE a big software program, following a set of coded rules.<br>
<br>
My second point: On The Ark<br>
<br>
Myths are a set of stories that communicate ideals and traditions of a society.  They are not to be taken literally, although they may contain elements of truth.  The myth about the ark, the myth about Abraham sacrificing Isaac, the myth about the tower of Babel, these are all stories with a COMMUNICATION value.  They tell about a society's values.  <br>
<br>
The Catholic Church has never had a problem not taking Bible Stories literally.  Being very well educated, yet deeply pious and devoted to God at once, they recognize these Myths to teach us HOW we are supposed to live our lives and why.  <br>
<br>
In 1996, the Pope declared that evolution possesses enough scientific evidence that it demands our attention, and is worthy or study and consideration.  He did not say we should accept it or deny it, merely consider it as possible truth.  Catholicism is not the archaic stupid institution that American youth love to make it out to be.  People really ought to learn more about it before they flame it. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/uwyndigomoonhowler.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Wyndigo Moonhowler</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 107<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/12/02 6:01:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=858.topic&index=32>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: bleh</span><hr size=1> Ayiar, it's ok for people to discuss religion if they can handle it and not start flaming or threatening each other.  I think open forums on this subject are great, and highly appropriate, considering we are playing a fantasy game based on myths from human cultures.  I would also think that people that play EQ have some sort of imagination or belief in the unseen, unless of course you are the kind of person that uses parsers, show eq, and other programs that reduces the game to code. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
