<br>
Want a universal truth about theories:  The theory which is the simplest, all other things being equal, will yield the most explanatory power. <br>
<br>
The same might be true about religions. So much diversity exist in the practice of religion. Diversity that ends in simplicity, I believe, is of the most service to people. It enables them to explain more about their lives and how reference and perspective can be gained before death. <br>
<br>
On the flipside, religion which seeks to cover souls with a shroud of guilt and which are not enabling theologies, often have elaborate and extremely complex &quot;teachings&quot; which obfuscate basic truths and therein lies their basic weakness:  Their complexity. <br>
<br>
A lifetime can be consumed in the minute study of individual religions. I have always tried to step away from the specific in the case of religions and examine the general topic of &quot;religion&quot; from a holistic perspective. Ask what functions religions perform and then see which religion has theoretic constructs that are simple and elegant in their form. <br>
<br>
It's like judging a house from the outside when you accept as a given that the simplest designs yield the most shelter and comfort for the occupants. 8-)<br>
<br>
